}}'''EDSA''', Inc. (previously known as [[Edward Durell Stone, Jr.]], and Associates) is a planning, [[landscape architecture]], and [[urban design]] firm founded in 1960.<ref name="edsaplan1">http://www.edsaplan.com/files/media-download/press_room/edsa-edsa-fact-sheet-2145.pdf</ref> 
The company is headquartered in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]] with offices in [[Orlando, Florida]]; [[Manhattan, New York]]; [[Baltimore, Maryland]]; and [[Shanghai, China]].<ref name="edsaplan1" />

There are 120 employees who represent EDSA and come from a varied range of cultural and ethnic distinctiveness with origins from more than 25 different countries. In addition, their portfolio spans a global range of more than 500 projects in over 100 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.e-architect.co.uk/architects/edsa-landscape-architects |title=EDSA Landscape Architects - USA |publisher=e-architect |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref> The firm has been referred to as one of the leading landscape architecture companies in the world.<ref name="miamiherald1">{{cite web|last=Morrissey |first=Siobhan |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2013/07/07/3489495/landscape-architecture-firm-edsa.html |title=Landscape architecture firm EDSA is grounded in urban design - Business Monday |publisher=MiamiHerald.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref>

EDSA also considers itself a steward of the land, according to the website, and places [[sustainability]] at the forefront of its planning and design efforts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edsaplan.com/en/Insight/Philosophy/Sustainability |title=Sustainability &#124; EDSA |publisher=Edsaplan.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://robbreport.com/LuxuryNewswire/luxury-travel/edsa-unveils-new-global-projects-showcasing-sustainable-design |title=EDSA Unveils New Global Projects Showcasing Sustainable Design &#124; Robb Report - The Global Luxury Source |publisher=Robb Report |date=2013-10-15 |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref> EDSA services include: Master Planning ([[Site selection]] and [[site analysis]], land use planning, [[feasibility studies]], visioning workshops, development strategies, site-specific plans, design guidelines and entitlements), [[Landscape Architecture]] (Site design and theming, conceptual and schematic design, design development, [[hardscape]] and water features, planting design and construction period services), and [[Urban Design]] (Downtown planning, city revitalization and redevelopment, urban open space, transit-oriented design, public consensus building and vision plans).<ref name="edsaplan1" />

== History ==

EDSA was founded in 1960 by American landscape architect Edward Durell Stone, Jr., who collaborated with his father, architect [[Edward Durell Stone]], Sr. to found EDSA.  Stone, Jr. died in 2009 and Douglas C. Smith, who joined the firm in 1987, now serves as president of the company.<ref>[[Edward Durell Stone, Jr.]]</ref>

In the 1960s, EDSA became an instrumental player in the travel and [[tourism]] industries, leading resort and recreation assignments primarily in the [[Caribbean]], [[Latin America]], and the [[Southeastern United States]]. During this time, EDSA adopted an environmentally-based design philosophy, which was a relatively obscure notion that takes inspiration from each project's local heritage. A village center form became the framework for housing, amenities, and commerce in order to conserve resources and foster social diversity. This approach became a hallmark of EDSA resorts and communities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edsaplan.com/homepage.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050605012408/http://www.edsaplan.com/homepage.html |archivedate=2005-06-05 |title=About EDSA}}</ref>

In 1971, EDSA began to receive national recognition when Stone, Jr. was appointed to the [[Commission of Fine Arts]] in Washington, D.C. by President [[Richard Nixon]]. He served in the position for 12 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tclf.org/pioneer/edward-stone-jr |title=Edward Stone, Jr. &#124; The Cultural Landscape Foundation |publisher=Tclf.org |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref> Simultaneously, EDSA's reach was growing on an international level as the firm expanded within the global marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive-com.com/page/2069145/2013-05-12/http://www.worldarchitecturenews.com/index.php?fuseaction=wanappln.showbriefdetail&newsid=1916 |title=World Architecture News: EDSA expands into Asia with Shanghai office |publisher=Archive-com.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref> Assignments in the Middle East, Europe, and South America further imbedded the values of sensitivity to local cultures and the importance of collaboration with local professionals.

EDSA broadened its urban design practice with two influential public commissions that reinvigorated Fort Lauderdale's neglected urban waterfronts: The Fort Lauderdale Beach Revitalization in 1986 and Riverwalk Linear Park which was completed in 1994.<ref name="miamiherald1"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cityviewfortlauderdale.com/archived-articles/2-uncategorised/277-the-death-of-spring-break-by-rob-dressler |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-04-24 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140424160050/http://www.cityviewfortlauderdale.com/archived-articles/2-uncategorised/277-the-death-of-spring-break-by-rob-dressler |archive-date=2014-04-24 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>

In the 1990s, EDSA embarked on planning for several academic institutions including the [[College of Staten Island]] and [[Nova Southeastern University]] as well as cultural venues like the Florida Nature Cultural Center. A branch office in Orlando began to thrive with several assignments for the [[Disney Corporation]] and the new [[Orlando International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northstarpubs.com/articles/lab/linquist-appointed-principal-at-edsa |title=Linquist Appointed Principal At EDSA &#124; Northstar Publishing |publisher=Northstarpubs.com |date=2013-09-26 |accessdate=2014-08-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808053732/http://www.northstarpubs.com/articles/lab/linquist-appointed-principal-at-edsa |archive-date=2014-08-08 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>
In 1994, Joseph Lalli became President of EDSA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://landscapeonline.com/research/article/12027 |title=Article : Global Reach, Village Comfort; Profile: Joseph Lalli, FASLA, President and Managing Principal of EDSA |publisher=LandscapeOnline.com |date= |accessdate=2014-08-04}}</ref>  Under his leadership, EDSA Orient became the first joint venture landscape architectural office in [[Beijing]], China.  He took the role of Chairman from 2012 until 2014, when he died. Currently, J. Robert Behling holds the role of Chairman.

